Got it üëç I‚Äôll put everything together for you:

SQL Server Stored Procedure

Web.config connection string

ASPX Page (with modal + alert + auto-hide)

Code-behind (C# save logic with stored procedure)



---

üîπ 1. SQL Server Stored Procedure

Run this in your database (adjust column sizes if needed):

CREATE PROCEDURE sp_InsertMeeting
    @Title NVARCHAR(200),
    @StartDate DATE,
    @StartTime TIME,
    @EndDate DATE,
    @EndTime TIME,
    @Location NVARCHAR(200),
    @Organizer NVARCHAR(200)
AS
BEGIN
    SET NOCOUNT ON;

    INSERT INTO tbl_meetings (Title, StartDate, StartTime, EndDate, EndTime, Location, Organizer)
    VALUES (@Title, @StartDate, @StartTime, @EndDate, @EndTime, @Location, @Organizer);
END

‚ö° Make sure your table tbl_meetings has the columns:
Title, StartDate, StartTime, EndDate, EndTime, Location, Organizer.


---

üîπ 2. Web.config Connection String

<configuration>
  <connectionStrings>
    <add name="MyDB"
         connectionString="Data Source=YOUR_SERVER;Initial Catalog=YOUR_DATABASE;Integrated Security=True"
         providerName="System.Data.SqlClient" />
  </connectionStrings>
</configuration>

üëâ Replace YOUR_SERVER and YOUR_DATABASE with your actual SQL Server details.
If using SQL login, use:

connectionString="Data Source=YOUR_SERVER;Initial Catalog=YOUR_DATABASE;User ID=sa;Password=yourpassword"


